In [[Ancient Roman]] entertainment, the term '''''acroama''''' ([[Greek language|Gr]]: <!--Wikipedia Template {{polytonic|ἀκρόαμα}} -->) referred to anything heard, and especially any thing heard with pleasure, such as a [[play]] or [[music]]al piece; hence a [[concert]] of players on different musical instruments, and also an [[interlude]], called ''embolia'' by [[Cicero]] ([[:s:la:Pro Sestio#.5BLIV.5D|''Pro Sestio'' 54]]), which was performed during the exhibition of the public games.

The word is also applied to the actors and musicians who were employed to amuse guests during an entertainment; and it is sometimes used to designate the [[anagnostae]].

